JOHANNESBURG - The new moon has not been sighted in Saudi Arabia and Muslims around the world will have to wait a bit longer to mark the start of Ramadan. Ramadan, the holiest month on the Islamic calendar, marks the start of the 30-day fast. In South Africa, the expectation always was that Ramadan would start on Thursday. The holy period is expected to run into mid-June. IN PICTURES: Muslims around the world celebrate Eid al-Fitr During this period, practicing Muslims who are able to, are barred from eating between sunrise and sunset. The aim of the fast is to help teach Muslims self-restraint, discipline and generosity. There are over 1,5 billion Muslims worldwide. eNCA